\begin_layout Section
Aim of the experiment
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The aim of the experiment is to measure the angle of repose of a material
 as a function of the diameter of the base of the pile.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Theory
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A granular material can be often heaped into a conical pile without slumping.
 It's angle of repose 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is then defined as the angle that the slanting edge of the cone makes with
 the horizontal such that a grain particle on the slope is just on the verge
 of moving (slipping/rolling) down.
 It has been observed that the angle of repose depends upon the density
 of the material, size, shape and surface area of the material and its coefficie
nt of friction.
 Generally, 
\begin_inset Formula $30^{0}<\alpha<45^{0},$
\end_inset

 though there are several exceptions, especially for mixtures and wet materials
 where adhesive forces and fluid properties like surface tension come into
 the picture.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The simplest model involves theorizing a grain particle on the pile of the
 material as a rigid block sliding down a rough inclined plane.
 In this case, if the coefficient of friction is 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu,$
\end_inset

 the block will start sliding down the inclined if the angle of inclined
\begin_inset Formula $>\mbox{tan}^{-1}\mu$
\end_inset

 .
 Therefore, 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=\mbox{tan}^{-1}\mu.$
\end_inset

 Since 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu$
\end_inset

 is rarely greater than 
\begin_inset Formula $1,$
\end_inset

 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha$
\end_inset

 is rarely 
\begin_inset Formula $>45^{0}.$
\end_inset

 
\end_layout

